article.description:
Utah won its second straight to move into a tie with the
Nuggets.
article.headline: Bell, Kirilenko score 18 apiece
article.linkText: Jazz beat Hawks, move into tie with Nuggets
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- The Utah Jazz know they can't finish the regular season in a tie with Denver. If they want to beat out the Nuggets for a playoff spot, they'll have to finish ahead of them -- which makes games such as Saturday's so important. Raja Bell and Andrei Kirilenko each scored 18 points, and the Jazz won for the fifth time in seven games -- 87-81 over the Hawks. Utah won its second straight to move into a tie with the Nuggets. Denver, which owns the tiebreaker by virtue of a 3-0 lead in the season series, was idle and plays Sunday at Minnesota. "It's a pretty good feeling," said Andrei Kirilenko, who had 18 points, 10 rebounds, seven assists and four blocks. "Everybody can play good basketball and everybody can beat us, especially with a team that is right now out of the playoff picture. We have a pretty good group of guys right now and the chemistry is right." Bell was still agonizing over a four-point loss Wednesday at Toronto. Three days earlier, the Jazz lost to the Nuggets. "We've got Denver at home again," Bell said. "Maybe we can turn the tables on them this time." Bob Sura had 19 points to lead the Hawks, who have lost two straight, four of five and eight of 10. Atlanta had won two straight at home against the Jazz, but Utah won for the 10th time in the teams' last 12 matchups. Sura endured a terrible final minute. After missing an 18-footer in front of the Hawks' bench that could've made it a three-point game, Sura fouled Kirilenko with one second left on the shot clock. Kirilenko hit the ensuing free throws to put Utah ahead 85-78. "We didn't execute down the stretch," Sura said. "We were hanging in there. We had some wide-open shots. They're a good team, a playoff team, and we battled hard." The Jazz led from early in the first quarter until Jason Terry's foul line jumper put the Hawks up 48-47 with 9:23 left in the third. Atlanta was ahead 72-65 with 10:31 remaining after Boris Diaw's tomahawk dunk, but Utah went on an 18-4 run that culminated with Jason Collier's turnover and Raul Lopez's reverse layup with 3:52 left. Jazz coach Jerry Sloan was upset by his team's lackadaisical play early in the fourth quarter. "One time, the ball was lying loose down there. We had three guys with a chance at it and we ran away from it," Sloan said. "I don't understand that. If you think you want to be a playoff team, you don't let things like that happen to you." The Hawks, who misfired on their first six 3-point attempts, finished 2-of-17 from beyond the arc as Jason Terry and Stephen Jackson combined to go 0-of-12. Atlanta shot 30.8 percent from the floor in the last period. "We're a jump shooting team, and two games in a row, we haven't shot the ball very well," Hawks coach Terry Stotts said. "That's part of our game." Atlanta doomed itself with six turnovers in the fourth quarter, including two straight after Collier's jumper from the top of the key made it 83-78. "I think fatigue set in a little bit, but that's not an excuse," Terry said. "The Jazz -- they're in the playoff hunt and they wanted it a little more than we did tonight." Utah, which improved to 13-23 on the road, hosts Washington on Tuesday and visits Seattle on Wednesday before the Nuggets visit the Delta Center next Saturday.

Game notes
The Jazz are now 10-5 since acquiring Tom Gugliotta from Phoenix and Gordan Giricek from Orlando. ... Hawks F Chris Crawford missed his third straight game with a sprained left thumb. ... Wesley Person, playing in just his seventh game since Atlanta acquired in a Feb. 9 trade with Portland, hit the Hawks' only two 3s.
